      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Shrinkage, you say? High shrinkage, like a horde of mischievous little goblins raiding your stockroom, pilfering your goods! *Hmph*. Don't worry your head about it; I've seen worse inventory chaos than a goblin raid on a poorly secured pile of shiny trinkets.\n\nTo factor shrinkage into your inventory turnover ratio, you essentially need to adjust your Cost of Goods Sold (COGS) to reflect what you *actually* sold versus what you *should* have sold. Think of it like this: if your inventory is shrinking faster than a goblin can sneak past a sleeping troll, your reported sales figures are misleading.\n\nThe standard formula for Inventory Turnover is:\n\n$$\\text{Inventory Turnover} = \\frac{\\text{Cost of Goods Sold (COGS)}}{\\text{Average Inventory}}$$\n\nWhen shrinkage is a factor, you need to adjust the numerator (COGS). Instead of using the raw COGS, you should use an **Adjusted COGS**.\n\n$$\\text{Adjusted COGS} = \\text{Reported COGS} + \\text{Cost of Shrinkage}$$\n\nThe Cost of Shrinkage is calculated by taking the value of the goods lost due to",
