      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A \"goblin raid,\" you ask? Well, my friend, in the world of inventory, shrinkage *is* a goblin raid! It's those sneaky little pests—theft, errors, spoilage—that sneak into your stock like a band of hungry, green-skinned goblins looking for shiny things. They don't just *disappear*; they are *taken*, and that's what we need to account for!\n\nNow, to finish that formula, you need to calculate the **Cost of Shrinkage**. This is where you quantify the damage done by those little inventory bandits.\n\n$$\\text{Cost of Shrinkage} = (\\text{Beginning Inventory Value} + \\text{Purchases Value}) - \\text{Ending Inventory Value} - \\text{COGS (Reported)}$$\n\nOr, more simply, if you know the physical count versus the system count, you find the difference in value. You take the value of the goods that *should* be there (based on what you bought and started with) and subtract what you *actually* have left at the end. The gap? That's the goblin loot!\n\nOnce you have that dollar amount for the Cost of",
