      "content": "Oh, the terminology! It's just that in my experience, any unexplained loss in a warehouse smells suspiciously like a goblin infestation. They are masters of misdirection, much like a particularly cunning goblin chieftain trying to hide his hoard!\n\nTo answer your very precise question about where that \"loot\"—the Cost of Shrinkage—goes: you **add it to the Cost of Goods Sold (COGS)** in the numerator of the turnover ratio. You do *not* subtract it from the average inventory, though you *could* adjust the inventory figure itself, adding the shrinkage to the cost side is usually the clearest way to show the true cost of the goods that left your shelves.\n\nSo, the final, robust formula you need for your quarterly report is:\n\n$$\\text{Adjusted Inventory Turnover} = \\frac{\\text{Reported COGS} + \\text{Cost of Shrinkage}}{\\text{Average Inventory}}$$\n\nSee? By adding the shrinkage cost to the COGS, you are telling the reader, \"Hey, we *thought* we sold X amount, but because those little sneaky goblins stole Y amount, the *real* cost of what left our building was X plus Y!\" It gives a",
